types.name: Valence
types.description:
Qualitative feeling associated to a feedback item.

These enum variants are meant to be used only to control the appearance of feedback items.
They might not all be applicable in every context,
and their precise interpretation may depend on the context.
However, they are all intentionally gathered together for simplicity.

enumValues.name: SUCCESS
enumValues.description:
A successful result.
E.g., a award is given full score.

enumValues.name: PARTIAL
enumValues.description:
A partial success.
E.g., a award is given partial score.

enumValues.name: FAILURE
enumValues.description:
A failed result.
E.g., time limit exceeded causes the loss of an award.

enumValues.name: WARNING
enumValues.description:
The user should pay attention to something because it could result in a future failure.
E.g., memory usage approaches the limit.

enumValues.name: NOMINAL
enumValues.description:
An operation is completed successfully, as usually expected.
E.g., a submitted source compiles correctly.

enumValues.name: SKIPPED
enumValues.description:
An operation is not performed, because a previous _success_ makes it unnecessary.
E.g., an award is not evaluated because already achieved.

enumValues.name: IGNORED
enumValues.description:
An operation is not performed, because irrelevant in the context.
E.g., the compilation of a source program written in Python is note performed.

enumValues.name: BLOCKED
enumValues.description:
An operation is not performed, because a previous _failure_ makes it unnecessary.
E.g., a large test case is not evaluated because a solution fails in a smaller one.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description:
GraphQL type kind

The GraphQL specification defines a number of type kinds - the meta type of a type.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description:
## Scalar types

Scalar types appear as the leaf nodes of GraphQL queries. Strings, numbers, and booleans are the built in types, and while it's possible to define your own, it's relatively uncommon.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description:
## Object types

The most common type to be implemented by users. Objects have fields and can implement interfaces.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description:
## Interface types

Interface types are used to represent overlapping fields between multiple types, and can be queried for their concrete type.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description:
## Union types

Unions are similar to interfaces but can not contain any fields on their own.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description:
## Enum types

Like scalars, enum types appear as the leaf nodes of GraphQL queries.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description:
## Input objects

Represents complex values provided in queries _into_ the system.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description:
## List types

Represent lists of other types. This library provides implementations for vectors and slices, but other Rust types can be extended to serve as GraphQL lists.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description:
## Non-null types

In GraphQL, nullable types are the default. By putting a `!` after a type, it becomes non-nullable.
